{
  "answer": "**In Yājñavalkya Smṛti 3.40, no penance (*prāyaścitta*) is prescribed.**[^1]\n\nThis verse, in the section on \"Duties in Times of Distress\" (*āpaddharmaprakaraṇam*), instead prohibits a Brahmin (even when resorting to a Vaiśya's occupation) from selling lac, salt, and meat; it states that selling milk, curd, or liquor causes one to become of a lower *varṇa*.[^2] The surrounding verses list further prohibited sales (3.36–39)[^3] and note that a distressed Brahmin accepting food from any source is not tainted by sin (3.41),[^4] but 3.40 itself specifies no expiatory rite.\n\n[^1]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, ch.3 [p-6d9cb4](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/03/translation/#p-6d9cb4).\n[^2]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, ch.3 [p-6d9cb4](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/03/translation/#p-6d9cb4).\n[^3]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, ch.3 [p-a9755d](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/03/translation/#p-a9755d) to [p-6d9cb4](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/03/translation/#p-6d9cb4).\n[^4]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, ch.3 [p-c03f6a](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/03/translation/#p-c03f6a).",
